</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="183.[189,1399,1315,1494]" pageId="183" pageNumber="184">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shiraki" authorityYear="1930" box="[189,639,1315,1341]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="183" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varidissima" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[189,639,1315,1341]" italics="true" pageId="183" pageNumber="184">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) varidissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is dissimilar to other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stackelberg" authorityYear="1974" box="[1060,1218,1315,1341]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="183" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[1060,1218,1315,1341]" italics="true" pageId="183" pageNumber="184">Asiosphegina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the colour and pollinosity of the scutum and the overall brownish colour. It resembles somewhat 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="183" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerina" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="183" pageNumber="184">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) cerina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in body colour but differs by the characters mentioned in the key. The male genitalia are unique, especially the symmetrical superior lobes which are basally narrowed, and which are separated from sternum IX by a transverse crest-like lobe posteriorly on the latter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
