<paragraph blockId="186.[189,1399,266,327]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
IV, 
<figureCitation box="[233,344,266,292]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="184.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[191,1395,932,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@184.[189,1399,925,1889]" captionTargetPageId="184" captionText="Fig. 94. Sphegina (Asiosphegina) varidissima Shiraki, 1930, Ƌ Fuhsing, Taiwan. A. Sterna IV and VI, ventral view. B. Left surstylus and superior lobe with associated parts, lateral view. C. Genitalia, right side, lateral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3830754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3830754/files/figure.png" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Fig. 94A</figureCitation>
; sterna VI, VII and VIII simple, with long yellow pile. Genitalia, 
<figureCitation box="[1144,1232,266,292]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="184.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[191,1395,932,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@184.[189,1399,925,1889]" captionTargetPageId="184" captionText="Fig. 94. Sphegina (Asiosphegina) varidissima Shiraki, 1930, Ƌ Fuhsing, Taiwan. A. Sterna IV and VI, ventral view. B. Left surstylus and superior lobe with associated parts, lateral view. C. Genitalia, right side, lateral view. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3830754" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3830754/files/figure.png" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Fig. 94</figureCitation>
B–C: note the almost symmetrical surstyli and superior lobes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,827,367,428]" box="[234,531,367,393]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,531,367,393]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Redescription of female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,827,367,428]" box="[189,827,402,428]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Similar to the male except normal sexual dimorphism.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,725,468,494]" box="[189,725,468,494]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
LENGTH. Body 
<quantity box="[362,506,468,494]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.6" metricValueMax="7.8" metricValueMin="7.4" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" unit="mm" value="7.6" valueMax="7.8" valueMin="7.4">7.4–7.8 mm</quantity>
, wing 
<quantity box="[584,725,468,494]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.4" metricValueMax="6.7" metricValueMin="6.1" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" unit="mm" value="6.4" valueMax="6.7" valueMin="6.1">6.1–6.7 mm</quantity>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,1399,534,738]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
HEAD. Lateral view, 
<figureCitation box="[433,533,534,560]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="170.[189,232,1821,1847]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,457,1781]" captionTargetId="figure@170.[189,1399,457,1781]" captionTargetPageId="170" captionText="Fig. 88. Head. lateral view (C, E, F, J) and dorsal view (A–B, D, G–I, K–L). A. Sphegina (Asiosphegina) spathigera sp. nov., holotype, Ƌ, Philippines. B–C. S. (A.) spenceri sp. nov., paratype, Ƌ, Vietnam. D–E. S. (A.) strigillata sp. nov., holotype, Ƌ, Vietnam. F. S. (A.) tricoloripes, Brunetti, 1915, ♀, India. G. S. (A.) tricoloripes, Ƌ, India. H. S. (A.) umbrosa sp. nov., holotype, Ƌ, China. I. S. (A.) varidissima Shiraki, 1930, Ƌ, Taiwan. J. S. (A.) varidissima, ♀, Taiwan. K. S. (A.) verrucosa sp. nov., paratype, Ƌ, Vietnam. L. S. (A.) vietnamensis sp. nov., paratype, Ƌ, Vietnam. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3830732" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3830732/files/figure.png" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Fig. 88J</figureCitation>
; ratio width of vertex at anterior ocellus: width of head 1: 3.0–3.4; ratio width of ocellar triangle: width of vertex 1: 2.6–2.9; ratio length of ocellar triangle: length of frons 1: 4.1–4.5. Mouth edge yellow. Face entirely yellow (as in 
<typeStatus box="[861,966,605,631]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">holotype</typeStatus>
) to predominantly black. Frons subshiny, slightly grey pollinose, with wide but weak medial furrow. Scape and pedicel yellow or black. Basoflagellomere black squarish, ratio width: length 1: 0.86–0.98; arista short pilose basally; about 3 times as long as basoflagellomere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,1398,777,874]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">THORAX. Scutellum black with posterior margin narrowly pollinose, rest non-pollinose and shiny, with two very widely set, long setae medially at posterior margin, ratio length of scutellum: length of seta 1: 2.0–2.3.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,774,914,940]" box="[189,774,914,940]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">WING. Microtrichose, cell cup with basal 1/10 bare.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,1399,980,1077]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">LEGS. Pro- and mesotibia dark yellow; pro- and mesobasitarsus dark brown, other tarsomeres dark brown to black; metafemur ratio width: length 1: 4.1–4.3; metatarsus with basitarsomere thin, ratio width: length 1: 3.8–4.1.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,1399,1117,1356]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">ABDOMEN. Length ratio of terga I: II: III: IV: V 1: 3.0–3.4: 2.4–2.7: 2.2–2.5: 1.1–1.3; ratio width at posterior margin: medial length of tergum II and III 1: 1.2–2.4 and 1: 0.6–0.7. Tergum II black or with posterolateral orange subtriangular macula; tergum III black to orange-brown with small black anteromedial macula; tergum IV yellow with anteromedial black macula to entirely orange-brown; tergum V entirely orange-brown; sternum III trapezoidal, ratio width: length 1: 2.5–2.7; sternum IV rectangular, ratio width: length 1: 0.9–1.1; sternum V rectangular with concave posterior margin, ratio width: length 1: 0.4–0.5.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="186" pageNumber="187" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,303,1396,1422]" box="[189,303,1396,1422]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1396,1422]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1396,1422]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="186.[189,1399,1443,1540]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">
The species is, as several Palaearctic species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Shiraki, 1968" authorityName="Shiraki" authorityYear="1968" box="[788,1349,1443,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciata" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis box="[788,1183,1443,1469]" italics="true" pageId="186" pageNumber="187">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) fasciata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Shiraki T." box="[1190,1349,1443,1469]" pageId="186" pageNumber="187" refId="ref92680" refString="Shiraki T. 1968. Fauna Japonica, Syrphidae (Insecta: Diptera). Vol. III. Biogeographical Society of Japan, Tokyo." type="book" year="1968">Shiraki, 1968</bibRefCitation>
